      "title": "Response",
      "uuid": "3f37c85629db4af192cb9cf7bc93caf0",
      "x": -2642.2349193526316,
      "y": -137.9820676585814,
      "width": 420.0,
      "height": 1660.0,
      "z_value": 0.0,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "emoji": "\ud83d\ude2e",
      "label": "Not arbitrary at all \u2014 those are the exact token categories the Anthropic API reports back on every response. From your own JSONL data:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"input_tokens\": 3,\n  \"cache_creation_input_tokens\": 7231,\n  \"cache_read_input_tokens\": 12604,\n  \"output_tokens\": 28\n}\n```\n\nHere's what each means:\n\n- **Input tokens** \u2014 fresh tokens sent to the model, not cached. The actual new content in each request.\n- **Output tokens** \u2014 tokens Claude generated in the response.\n- **Cache creation** \u2014 tokens written INTO the prompt cache for the first time. When Claude Code sends your system prompt, CLAUDE.md, conversation history, etc., the API can cache that payload so the next request doesn't reprocess it. This is the \"write\" cost.\n- **Cache read** \u2014 tokens served FROM the cache on subsequent requests. This is the \"hit\" \u2014 same content, already processed, 90% cheaper than fresh input.\n\nFor this project: 83M cache creates vs 401M cache reads. That's roughly a 5:1 read-to-write ratio \u2014 the cache is doing serious work. Most of your conversation context is being reused across turns rather than reprocessed from scratch.\n\nThe info node reads these directly from `entry[\"message\"][\"usage\"]` in every assistant-type JSONL line across all sessions in the project folder. It's not hitting the API live \u2014 it's tallying what the API already reported.\n\nIf you want to start hitting the Anthropic API directly for live stats (like current billing, rate limits, or model availability), that's a different path \u2014 we'd use the `anthropic` SDK with your `SingleSharedBraincell_ApiKey`.",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
